abstract: Mr. Madoff, who ran the largest Ponzi scheme in history, told a court that he had less than 18 months to live.
snippet: Mr. Madoff, who ran the largest Ponzi scheme in history, told a court that he had less than 18 months to live.
lead_paragraph: Bernard L. Madoff, the mastermind of the largest Ponzi scheme in history, said in a court filing on Wednesday that he was dying and asked for an early release from prison.

abstract: The bill he supported is limited; it works by allowing people to borrow from their future selves.
snippet: The bill he supported is limited; it works by allowing people to borrow from their future selves.
lead_paragraph: President Trump called for paid family leave in the State of the Union on Tuesday, the first Republican president to do so. But the bill he supported does not offer what has generally been considered paid family leave.

headline_main: Nancy Pelosi (Literally) Rips Trump’s Speech Apart

abstract: In a pair of historic votes, 52 to 48 and 53 to 47, senators acquitted President Trump of two charges: abuse of power and obstruction of Congress.

headline_main: Senate Votes to Acquit President Trump

abstract: Readers discuss what it means for the president (“he can get away with anything”), and for the country. One says in jest that if democracy is over, he has a monarch to offer.

headline_main: In Private, Republicans Admit They Acquitted Trump Out of Fear
headline_print_headline: Republicans  Clear Trump Out of Fear

abstract: As Republicans rallied behind President Trump, Senator Mitt Romney of Utah, the party’s 2012 presidential nominee, joined Democrats in voting to convict, the only senator to cross party lines.
snippet: As Republicans rallied behind President Trump, Senator Mitt Romney of Utah, the party’s 2012 presidential nominee, joined Democrats in voting to convict, the only senator to cross party lines.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After five months of hearings, investigations and revelations about President Trump’s dealings with Ukraine, a divided United States Senate acquitted him on Wednesday of charges that he abused his power and obstructed Congress to aid his own re-election, bringing an acrimonious impeachment trial to its expected end.

headline_main: Trump Acquitted of Two Impeachment Charges in Near Party-Line Vote
headline_print_headline: Split Senate Clears Trump on Each Count in Finale of a Bitter Impeachment Battle

abstract: The president was acquitted by the Senate, but the American people are smarter.
snippet: The president was acquitted by the Senate, but the American people are smarter.
lead_paragraph: The vote to acquit President Trump was a dark day for the Senate. Uninterested in hearing from witnesses (and likely scared by what they would say), uncritical of outrageous legal arguments made by the president’s lawyers and apparently unconcerned about the damage Mr. Trump has done to the integrity of America’s elections, a majority of senators insisted on looking the other way and letting him off the hook for a classic impeachable offense: abuse of public office for private gain.

headline_main: Donald Trump, Cruise Ships, Avalanche: Your Thursday Briefing

abstract: Solid economic reports and corporate earnings bolstered equity and commodity markets.
snippet: Solid economic reports and corporate earnings bolstered equity and commodity markets.
lead_paragraph: A third straight day of gains on Wall Street on Wednesday raised stocks to a record, as investors took comfort in signs that the American economy was on solid footing despite risks tied to the spread of the coronavirus both inside and outside China.
